Controller buttons give a tactile click, but total travel is only ~1 mm and force profile is nearly constant—far short of the 4 cm push of a large button.
Rigid ceramic surface has zero displacement; no travel, spring, or activation feedback.
Rubber keys provide small travel and a soft tactile bump, but stroke length (<1 cm) and force curve do not approximate the deep, stiff push of a big button.
Primary mouse buttons click, giving confirmation, yet the travel is just millimetres with almost flat force ramp—insufficient for the 4 cm spring action.
Inverted cup flexes 2–4 cm with increasing resistance and partial snap-back, somewhat matching travel and force rise but still lacks a crisp detent.
Bristles compress only a few millimetres and feel soft, providing neither required travel nor a noticeable spring-loaded click.
Spring-loaded carry handle depresses ~2 cm with rising force and snaps back, giving a definite activation feel though stroke is shorter than 4 cm.
Tabletop is immovable; absolutely no perceivable travel or spring.
Pressing the base tilts the lamp slightly (<1 cm vertical displacement) with little resistance and no snap, so similarity to a big button is minimal.
Air-filled bag compresses several centimetres with increasing resistance and rebounds when released; however, deformation is squishy and lacks the final click.
Soil compresses unevenly and does not spring back; overall feel is nothing like a mechanical push-button.
Solid weight offers zero vertical travel; pushing only shoves the whole object without any compliant motion.
Some grinders allow a short springy press to grind pepper, giving slight resistance and click, but stroke is usually <1 cm—far below the desired 4 cm.
Bending or compressing the slender straw provides negligible vertical travel and no spring-back effect matching a button press.
Rigid PCB has no compressive travel; pressing only forces against a hard surface.
Strings depress a few millimetres before bottoming; they rebound but total motion and force ramp are far smaller than a 4 cm push-button stroke.
Foam compresses several centimetres with progressively rising force and rebounds fully; lacks a sharp detent but matches travel and spring qualities reasonably well.
Rigid wall-mounted surface offers no displacement or spring, giving none of the intended haptic feedback.
Curved profile and tapered ends produce no broad flat disc; mushy fruit compresses but with no spring-return or click.

explanation: Top is flat but square, only ~7 × 7 cm. Paper stack barely compresses (<1 mm) and lacks spring or detent.
Angular folds and hollow gaps—no circular palm-sized cap or controlled downward travel.
Top rim is circular but only ~4 cm across (half required). Tube can buckle ~4 cm with springy resistance, yet surface is narrow and edges dig into palm; no crisp click.
Controller face has small individual buttons; overall topography is irregular and too narrow for whole-palm press.
Diameter is large and circular but the plate is rigid—no downward travel, spring, or detent at all.
Multiple soft rubber keys yield tiny 1 mm travels, not a single 9 cm cap; outline and motion feel fragmented.
Hump roughly palm-width but click travel is <1 mm and occurs only at finger tips, not whole palm; no 4 cm stroke.

Base is circular (~5 cm) and flexes downward with springy walls and a slight pop when the base inverts, offering some button-like feel, though smaller diameter and less controlled stroke than required.
Tiny head, bristles compress only millimetres, and handle interferes—no resemblance to a 9 cm push-button.
Handle depresses into case with spring and audible click, but contact area is a narrow bar, not a broad disc.
Completely rigid; no movement or tactile transition—fails core requirements.
Circular base is the right shape but immovable; lamp only tilts, not a vertical 4 cm travel.
Air-filled bag compresses with springy feel and quick rebound, but outline is soft, irregular, and lacks the decisive click.
Soil gives way unpredictably; pot rim restricts palm; no spring return or consistent stroke.
End surface is too small (~5 cm) and the weight is completely rigid—zero travel.
Top presses down slightly when grinding (2-3 mm) with some detent, but diameter ~4 cm and requires twisting motion.
Contact disc is <1 cm; straw bends rather than translating; no spring-guided vertical travel.
Rigid electronics—no movement, no circular cap, sharp components hurt the palm.
Sound-hole diameter is close (10 cm) but strings resist only a few millimetres and quickly bottom out; no spring travel or click.
Large flat surface compresses 4-5 cm with foam spring and rebound; however area is too big, lacks circular edge and has no crisp detent.
Rigid wall-mounted board provides no vertical motion—fails fundamental button feel.
The banana in Snapshot 1 is clearly soft and easily deformable; when pressed it yields and bruises, offering none of the rigid surface expected from a hard button cap.

physicalObject: stack of neon green sticky notes
explanation: A compressed pad of paper feels firmer than loose sheets, but the stack still compresses several millimetres under palm pressure. It is noticeably less rigid than a plastic or metal button top.
Thin folded paper buckles almost immediately under load. The surface offers minimal resistance and therefore feels far too compliant compared with a rigid button.
The paper roll shown is hollow and visibly bends when pushed; its compliance is obvious and does not deliver the solid, non-yielding feel of a hard button cap.
The ABS plastic shell is stiff and does not compress under palm force. Although individual face buttons move, the bulk surface the hand contacts is rigid, matching button hardness well.
Glazed ceramic provides an extremely hard, non-deforming surface identical in feel to molded plastic or metal. It perfectly represents the rigid cap of the virtual button.
The housing is rigid plastic, but most palm contact lands on soft rubber keys that compress. Overall feel is harder than paper but noticeably softer in localized spots than a solid button top.
The main shell is thick ABS that does not flex under whole-palm pressure. Only small switch travel occurs at the buttons’ front edge, so perceived hardness is close to a rigid disc.
Thin PET walls visibly flex and crunch when pressed. The cup’s large elastic deformation feels soft and fragile—far from the rigid expectation of a button cap.
The handle is rigid, but the instructed contact area is the brush head; bristles collapse easily, introducing softness. The overall impression is firmer than paper yet softer than a true hard disc.
The plastic handle itself is rigid, but it moves on spring pivots and therefore yields a few millimetres when pressed. Hardness is moderate—hard material with slight compliance.
The tabletop is solid wood/particleboard and completely immovable under hand force, giving a perfectly rigid sensation that matches the desired hardness.
The metal/weighted base is clearly rigid and offers no surface give. It provides the same non-compliant feel expected from a robust plastic or metal button cap.
The air-filled bag squishes immediately with minimal force; it is the opposite of hardness and completely breaks the illusion of a rigid button.
The palm presses on loose soil, which compresses easily. While the ceramic rim is hard, the instructed utilization focuses on soil, so perceived hardness is low.
The cast-iron core is extremely rigid; the thin neoprene sleeve adds a slight cushion but overall feel remains very hard, close to the stiffness of a button cap.
Acrylic and metal body is rigid; only a small mechanical click occurs if grinding, but surface under palm does not compress, delivering high hardness fidelity.
Bamboo is hard, yet the thin tube can flex or buckle slightly when stood vertically. The limited structural stiffness reduces the perceived hardness somewhat.
The fiberglass PCB is stiff and components are soldered rigidly. Minor protrusions exist, but compliance is negligible, giving a hard, unmoving feel.
Pressing on tightened steel strings gives some resistance but they still deflect several millimetres. Underlying wood is rigid, yet the immediate contact has perceptible compliance.
The foam cushion compresses deeply; the surface is unmistakably soft and provides none of the rigid tactile qualities of a button cap.
The whiteboard’s melamine-coated hardboard is flat and completely rigid under hand pressure, replicating the non-yielding hardness of the virtual button perfectly.
